After serving briefly as professor of physics at the Dijon Lycée in 1848, he became professor of
chemistry at the University of Strasbourg,[

            ] where he met and courted Marie Laurent, daughter
of the university's rector in 1849. They were married on 29 May 1849,[36] and together had five
children, only two of whom survived to adulthood;[37] the other three died of typhoid.

